               Danubius, and the Rhine, Two eminent and principal Rivers, are put for the Country where they run, viz. Germany; ſo the Rhone and Loire for France: A figurative manner of Speech, common among Poets. I could give ſeveral Inſtances; but let one (out of Martial) ſuffice, Lib. 10. Ep. 26. to Varus, that Eminent Roman Commander;


Spargere non licuit frigentia fletibus ora,

Pinguia, nec maeſtis addere Thura Rogis;

Sed datur aeterno victurum carmine Nomen;

Nunquid & hoc fallax Nile negare potes?


                     Thus Tranſlated by Weaver.

We could not dew with Tears thy dying Face,

Nor thy ſad Funeral Flames with Odors grace:

Yet in my Verſe Eterniz'd thou ſhalt be;

Of That falſe Egypt cannot cozen Thee.

[Martial has it Nilus; Weaver, Egypt.]
